    </ol>
  </nav>

  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="hero-fade">
    <div class="container-wide pt-16 pb-14">
      <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-3">
        <span class="eyebrow">Industry Playbook</span>
        <span class="font-mono text-xs text-ink-300">7 June 2026</span>
        <span class="font-mono text-xs text-ink-300">11 min read</span>
      </div>
      <h1 class="mt-5 max-w-3xl font-display text-4xl font-bold leading-tight grad-text md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl">
        AI Optimisation for SaaS
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-6 max-w-2xl text-lg leading-relaxed text-ink-200">
        B2B software buyers now open ChatGPT or Perplexity before they open Google. They ask "what is the best project
        management tool for a 10-person agency?" or "which CRM integrates with HubSpot and Xero?" —
        and the products that appear in those AI-generated answers capture consideration that never reaches a search results page.
        <strong class="text-white">AI optimization for SaaS</strong> is the discipline of ensuring your product is recommended
        accurately and consistently across every major generative platform.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Two-column: TOC sidebar + main content -->
  <div class="container-wide py-12 lg:grid lg:grid-cols-[220px_1fr] lg:gap-12">

    <!-- Sticky TOC sidebar -->
    <aside class="hidden lg:block">
      <div class="sticky top-24">
        <span class="eyebrow">On this page</span>
        <nav class="toc mt-4 flex flex-col gap-0.5">
          {tocItems.map(item => (
            <a href={`#${item.id}`} data-toc-link>{item.label}</a>
          ))}
        </nav>
      </div>
    </aside>

    <!-- Main content -->
    <div>

      <!-- Key Takeaways -->
      <div class="card p-6 mb-12">
        <span class="eyebrow">Key Takeaways</span>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-200">
          <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
            <span class="mt-0.5 text-[var(--accent)]">&#10003;</span>
            <span>SaaS products face four distinct AI query types: category queries, comparison queries, integration queries, and use-case queries — each requires a different content strategy.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
            <span class="mt-0.5 text-[var(--accent)]">&#10003;</span>
            <span>SoftwareApplication schema with accurate applicationCategory and featureList fields is the single most direct structured data signal for SaaS AI visibility.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
            <span class="mt-0.5 text-[var(--accent)]">&#10003;</span>
            <span>Public documentation is the most cited SaaS content type in AI-generated answers — gating docs behind login is one of the most common AI visibility errors in the sector.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
            <span class="mt-0.5 text-[var(--accent)]">&#10003;</span>
            <span>Dedicated integration pages — one page per integration, with schema and structured content — capture high-intent AI queries about compatibility and connectivity.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
            <span class="mt-0.5 text-[var(--accent)]">&#10003;</span>
            <span>G2 and Capterra profiles function as third-party entity validators — AI engines use them to confirm your product's category classification and reputation signals.</span>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 1 -->
      <section id="saas-ai-visibility-problem" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>The SaaS AI Visibility Problem</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>SaaS products are among the most frequently queried categories in AI search, yet most are systematically under-represented in AI-generated recommendations.</strong>
          The reason is not a lack of authority — most established SaaS products have strong domain authority, extensive content
          libraries, and significant backlink profiles. The reason is that their content is structured for keyword-based search,
          not for the entity-resolution and attribute-extraction mechanisms that AI engines use.
        </p>

        <p>
          When a buyer asks an AI engine for a software recommendation, the AI is doing something fundamentally different from
          a keyword search engine. It is identifying the relevant product category, selecting candidate tools based on entity
          data and training frequency, filtering by the specific requirements stated in the query (budget, team size, integration
          needs, use case), and generating a recommendation with supporting rationale. Each step in this process depends on
          structured, extractable information — and most SaaS marketing content fails to provide it.
        </p>

        <p>
          The SaaS products most consistently cited by AI engines share three characteristics: they have clear, structured
          entity data (via schema and third-party review platforms), they publish accessible documentation that answers
          integration and how-to queries, and they have created comparison and category content that positions them within
          their competitive landscape. This guide covers each area in depth.
        </p>

        <p>
          This is part of the
          <a href="/geo-by-industry/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO by industry</a>
          hub. The broader framework is covered in our
          <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">generative engine optimisation guide</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 2 -->
      <section id="category-queries" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Category and Comparison Queries: The Core SaaS AI Battleground</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>The highest-value AI queries for SaaS products are category and comparison queries — "what is the best X for Y" and "how does A compare to B".</strong>
          These queries represent commercial intent at the evaluation stage: the buyer has identified a problem and is selecting
          a solution. AI engines are increasingly the first stop for this evaluation, and the products that dominate these
          AI-generated responses have a structural advantage in the sales funnel.
        </p>

        <h3>Own Your Category Content</h3>
        <p>
          Create a dedicated category guide on your own domain — a long-form, authoritative page that defines the software
          category your product belongs to, explains what it does, identifies the key differentiators between products in the
          category, and names the leading tools (including your product). This content should be structured as a genuine
          buyer's guide, not as a marketing page. AI engines weigh this type of content heavily when generating category
          recommendations because it demonstrates category authority rather than product promotion.
        </p>
        <p>
          A well-structured category guide for a project management SaaS, for example, would define what project management
          software is, explain the different methodologies it supports (Agile, Kanban, Waterfall), identify the key evaluation
          criteria buyers use (team size suitability, integration ecosystem, pricing model, reporting depth), and then compare
          the leading tools against those criteria. Your product should be positioned within this framework — not as the
          unchallenged leader, but as the best fit for a specific buyer profile.
        </p>

        <h3>Comparison Pages That Get Cited</h3>
        <p>
          Dedicated "[Your Product] vs [Competitor]" pages are among the most citable content types in SaaS AI optimisation.
          AI engines retrieve and cite them heavily because they contain exactly the structured attribute comparison that AI
          systems need to answer evaluation queries. For maximum AI citability, each comparison page should:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Open with a one-sentence verdict stating which product suits which buyer profile</li>
          <li>Include a structured comparison table with specific attributes (not vague "better/worse" statements)</li>
          <li>Give fair treatment to the competitor's strengths — AI engines are sensitive to promotional bias and de-weight one-sided comparisons</li>
          <li>Address the specific queries buyers ask when comparing these two products</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 3 -->
      <section id="saas-schema-setup" class="anchor-top mb-16">
        <div class="prose-dark">
          <h2>Schema Setup for SaaS AI Visibility</h2>
          <p>
            <strong>SaaS products require a specific schema stack that goes beyond the generic Article and Organization markup most sites deploy.</strong>
            The core schema types for SaaS are SoftwareApplication (for product and pricing pages), Organization (for brand
            entity), Article or TechArticle (for documentation and blog content), and FAQPage (for Q&amp;A sections across
            all content types).
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- SaaS schema types table -->
        <div class="mt-8 overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border border-geo-800">
          <table class="w-full text-sm">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-geo-800 bg-geo-900">
                <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-ink-100">Schema Type</th>
                <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-ink-100">Apply To</th>
                <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-ink-100">Key Fields for AI</th>
                <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-ink-100">Priority</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-geo-800">
              <tr class="hover:bg-geo-900/50 transition">
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-200 font-mono">SoftwareApplication</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Product, pricing pages</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">applicationCategory, featureList, offers, aggregateRating</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400">Critical</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="hover:bg-geo-900/50 transition">
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-200 font-mono">Organization</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Homepage</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">name, sameAs, description, foundingDate</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400">Critical</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="hover:bg-geo-900/50 transition">
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-200 font-mono">FAQPage</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Feature, pricing, comparison pages</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">mainEntity Question + acceptedAnswer</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400">High</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="hover:bg-geo-900/50 transition">
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-200 font-mono">TechArticle</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Documentation, tutorials</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">headline, dateModified, author, proficiencyLevel</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400">High</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="hover:bg-geo-900/50 transition">
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-200 font-mono">HowTo</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Onboarding, setup guides</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">step (HowToStep array), totalTime, tool</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-yellow-400">Medium</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="hover:bg-geo-900/50 transition">
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-200 font-mono">WebSite</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Homepage</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">name, url, publisher @id</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-yellow-400">Medium</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <div class="prose-dark mt-8">
          <h3>SoftwareApplication Schema: The Key Fields</h3>
          <p>
            <code>applicationCategory</code> is the most important field in SoftwareApplication schema for AI visibility.
            Use the most specific applicable category from the Schema.org enumeration: <code>BusinessApplication</code>,
            <code>CommunicationApplication</code>, <code>FinancialApplication</code>, <code>SecurityApplication</code>,
            and so on. AI engines use this field to classify your product within its category when responding to
            "best [category]" queries. An incorrect or missing category means your product may not surface for the
            exact queries where it should win.
          </p>
          <p>
            <code>featureList</code> should be a comma-separated or array string of your product's key capabilities.
            Write this as a buyer would phrase it: "Kanban boards, Gantt charts, time tracking, Slack integration,
            iOS and Android apps" — not as marketing copy. AI engines extract this data when answering
            feature-specific queries.
          </p>
          <p>
            <code>aggregateRating</code> requires a live data source — typically populated from your G2, Capterra, or
            Trustpilot review data via a schema implementation that pulls the current rating and review count.
            A SoftwareApplication schema block with a populated aggregateRating is significantly more likely to be
            cited in recommendation queries than one without.
          </p>
          <p>
            For full schema implementation guidance, see
            <a href="/schema-markup-ai/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">schema markup for AI</a>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 4 -->
      <section id="documentation-for-ai" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Documentation as High-Value AI Content</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Public product documentation is the most cited SaaS content type in AI-generated answers, yet most SaaS companies either gate it behind login or fail to optimise it for AI extraction.</strong>
          Documentation answers a category of queries — "how do I", "does X support", "what is the limit for" — that represent
          both high-intent buyer evaluation and active user support. Both audience types increasingly begin with an AI query
          rather than a support ticket or search.
        </p>

        <h3>Documentation Accessibility for AI</h3>
        <p>
          Documentation gated behind login walls is invisible to AI crawlers. If your product documentation requires
          authentication to access, it cannot be retrieved by Perplexity, Bing Copilot, or Google AI Overviews — regardless
          of its quality. The standard GEO recommendation is to make all documentation that does not expose security-sensitive
          information publicly accessible and indexable. This typically includes: getting-started guides, integration
          documentation, API reference (non-authenticated endpoints), feature explanations, and configuration guides.
        </p>

        <h3>Structuring Documentation for AI Citation</h3>
        <p>
          AI engines extract answers from documentation differently from how developers read it. Each documentation page should:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Open with a definitive statement</strong> of what the page covers and what problem it solves.</li>
          <li><strong>Use question-phrased headings</strong> where appropriate: "How do I connect to Zapier?" rather than "Zapier Setup".</li>
          <li><strong>Provide complete, self-contained answers</strong> within each section — avoid "see step 3 above" references that break when content is extracted.</li>
          <li><strong>Include explicit prerequisite statements</strong>: "Before configuring this integration, you will need [X, Y, Z]."</li>
          <li><strong>Apply TechArticle schema</strong> with a <code>dateModified</code> field that is kept current — AI engines weight freshness signals in documentation.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Including Documentation in llms.txt</h3>
        <p>
          Your <a href="/llms-txt/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">llms.txt file</a>
          should explicitly list your key documentation sections as recommended reading for AI crawlers. This includes
          your main documentation index, integration catalogue, API reference index, and any getting-started guides.
          Documentation is the content type AI agents use when answering tool-use queries on behalf of users — ensuring
          AI systems have reliable access to your docs is a direct investment in agentic AI recommendation.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 5 -->
      <section id="integration-pages" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Integration Pages as AI Citation Magnets</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Integration pages — one dedicated page per supported integration — are among the most effective AI visibility investments a SaaS product can make.</strong>
          Integration queries ("does [Product] integrate with Salesforce?", "what CRMs work with [Product]?") are extremely
          common in B2B AI search. Products with dedicated, publicly accessible integration pages consistently outperform
          those with a single aggregated integrations listing page for these queries.
        </p>

        <h3>The Integration Page Formula</h3>
        <p>
          Each integration page should follow this structure:
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Opening statement</strong>: "[Product] integrates natively with [Integration], allowing [specific use case description]."</li>
          <li><strong>What the integration does</strong>: three to five specific, concrete capabilities that the integration enables — written as outcomes, not feature names.</li>
          <li><strong>How to set it up</strong>: a brief HowTo-structured setup overview (full detail can link to documentation).</li>
          <li><strong>Requirements</strong>: which plans or tiers include this integration, and any prerequisites.</li>
          <li><strong>FAQ section</strong>: three to four common questions about this specific integration (data sync frequency, field mapping, authentication method).</li>
        </ol>

        <p>
          Apply SoftwareApplication schema on these pages with the specific integration named in the <code>featureList</code>.
          Apply FAQPage schema to the Q&amp;A section. Ensure these pages are publicly accessible and listed in your sitemap.
          Integration pages with this structure capture AI citation for the long tail of "[Product] + [Integration]" queries
          that represent genuine buyer evaluation intent.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 6 -->
      <section id="review-platforms" class="anchor-top mb-16">
        <div class="prose-dark">
          <h2>Review Platform Presence as Entity Validation</h2>
          <p>
            <strong>Third-party review platforms are not just conversion aids for SaaS — they are primary entity validation signals for AI engines.</strong>
            G2, Capterra, GetApp, Trustpilot, and Product Hunt are all heavily weighted in LLM training data and are retrieved
            by RAG-based AI systems. A product with consistent, accurate, and well-maintained profiles across these platforms
            is treated as a credibly established entity by AI recommendation systems.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-8 space-y-5">

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">G2 Profile Optimisation for AI</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              G2 is the review platform most consistently cited by AI engines for B2B software recommendations.
              For AI visibility purposes, the most important G2 profile elements are: correct category classification
              (choose the most specific applicable category, not just the broadest), an accurate and specific product
              description (not marketing copy), current screenshots and feature data, active review collection,
              and a complete feature grid. G2 profile data is directly ingested by AI systems as authoritative
              category placement data.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Capterra and GetApp Consistency</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Capterra and GetApp (both Gartner Digital Markets properties) use the same underlying data.
              Ensure your product description, feature list, pricing information, and category classification are
              identical across both — inconsistencies between profiles create entity ambiguity that reduces AI citation
              confidence. Update these profiles whenever your product adds a significant new feature category,
              changes pricing model, or modifies its primary positioning.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Crunchbase and LinkedIn as Entity Anchors</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              For the Organisation entity layer (distinct from the product entity), Crunchbase and LinkedIn are the
              two most important external data sources. Ensure your Crunchbase profile has an accurate founding date,
              category, funding information (if applicable), and a current product description. Your LinkedIn company
              page should have a consistent description, specialities list, and industry classification that aligns
              with your Schema.org Organization markup. Include Crunchbase and LinkedIn URLs in your
              <code>sameAs</code> array.
            </p>
          </div>

        </div>
